		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/10/02/anna-d-shapiro-named-artistic-director-of-steppenwolf-theater/" data-title="Anna D. Shapiro Named Artistic Director of Steppenwolf Theater" data-description="Ms. Shapiro, who has directed several acclaimed productions, will take over next fall from Martha Lavey, Steppenwolfâs longtime leader.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/03/arts/02artsbeat-anna/02artsbeat-anna-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/03/arts/02artsbeat-anna/02artsbeat-anna-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/03/arts/02artsbeat-anna/02artsbeat-anna-articleInline.jpg" id="100000003154190" width="190" height="227" alt="Anna D. Shapiro accepting the Tony Award for directing &quot;August: Osage County&quot; in 2008."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="227"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Anna D. Shapiro accepting the Tony Award for directing "August: Osage County" in 2008.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Sara Krulwich/The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One of the nationâs most prominent theaters, Steppenwolf Theater Company, is getting its first new artistic director in 20 years, executives at the Chicago theater announced on Thursday. Anna D. Shapiro, who has directed several acclaimed Steppenwolf productions â including the hit play <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2007/12/05/theater/reviews/05august.html?pagewanted=all">âAugust: Osage County,â</a> which transferred to Broadway and won her a Tony Award â will take over next fall for Martha Lavey, Steppenwolfâs longtime leader and an actor in Steppenwolfâs renowned ensemble of performers and artists.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At a news conference at Steppenwolf, Ms. Lavey said she would continue as an ensemble member. Known as a sharp judge of plays â Steppenwolf has steadily developed work that later found acclaim on Broadway and Off Broadway â Ms. Lavey was not widely known to be considering stepping down; The Chicago Tribune <a href="//www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/theater/chi-martha-lavey-steppenwolf-anna-d-shapiro-column.html">characterized the decision</a> as a âsurpriseâ on Thursday. Ms. Lavey indicated that the time for transition was right for both her and Ms. Shapiro as well as for Steppenwolf, which is intensifying efforts to raise $55 million to support a long-planned theater expansion. About one-third of that money has been raised so far.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âShe is ready to lead Steppenwolf,â Ms. Lavey said in a statement about Ms. Shapiro. âI am enormously proud to hand over the stewardship of this treasured company to Anna.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Shapiro, who has been courted by other theaters over the years for leadership positions, has been <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/02/03/theater/female-directors-more-prominent-in-new-york.html?pagewanted=all">working increasingly in New York</a>, but her family is based in Chicago and she also teaches at Northwestern. She is currently represented on Broadway by <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/09/12/theater/this-is-our-youth-stars-michael-cera-kieran-culkin-and-tavi-gevinson.html">âThis Is Our Youth,â</a> a revival of Kenneth Lonerganâs play about young people at loose ends in 1980s Manhattan, which she first directed at Steppenwolf this summer. She is also set to direct âFish in the Dark,â Larry Davidâs new play, on Broadway this winter. Ms. Shapiroâs other Broadway credits include last seasonâs revival of âOf Mice and Men,â starring James Franco, and the Tony-nominated 2011 play <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2011/04/12/theater/reviews/the-with-the-hat-by-stephen-adly-guirgis-review.html?pagewanted=all">âThe ___________ With the Hatâ</a> by Stephen Adly Guirgis, which starred Chris Rock.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Shapiro, who is 48, frequently collaborates with two Pulitzer Prize-winning playwrights, Bruce Norris (most recently on <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/11/05/theater/reviews/in-domesticated-with-jeff-goldblum-a-power-couple-duels.html?pagewanted=all">âDomesticatedâ</a>) and Mr. Letts (âAugust: Osage County,â âSuperior Donutsâ), both of whom are also members of Steppenwolf. Founded in 1974, Steppenwolfâs ensemble includes Joan Allen, Terry Kinney, John Malkovich, Laurie Metcalf, Amy Morton, Jeff Perry and Gary Sinise.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âSteppenwolf has always been at the center of everything in my professional life,â Ms. Shapiro said in a statement.  âIt has been my distinct honor to work alongside Martha Lavey since we both came onto the artistic staff 19 years ago and I feel very fortunate that our wishes for the company, as well as the evolution of our own lives, has led us to the transition together.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Also announced on Thursday, Steppenwolfâs managing director, David M. Schmitz, will become the theaterâs executive director in January, overseeing management of the company and the expansion of Steppenwolfâs theater and rehearsal space over the next several years. He will succeed David Hawkanson, who will continue to work with the theater on an advisory basis, particularly on the expansion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Based on its most recent annual tax returns that are publicly available, Steppenwolf has had a mix of budget surpluses and deficits over the last few years â fairly common for nonprofit theaters, especially since the 2008 recession. The theaterâs current annual budget is about $15 million. The Tribune reported that Steppenwolf has been slow to raise funds for the expansion, finding that private sources of money have become hard to tap in the current economy and in a city with competition from many other arts institutions like the Goodman Theater and scores of other stage companies. </p>
<footer class="story-footer">
    <div class="story-meta">
	<p class="story-print-citation">A version of this article appears in print on 10/03/2014, on page <span itemprop="printSection">C</span><span itemprop="printPage">2</span> of the <span itemprop="printEdition">NewYork</span> edition with the headline: New Artistic Director For Steppenwolf.</p>    </div>
</footer>
	</div>
